  "opinion": "As a woman who's spent most of her life in the workforce without a college degree, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can silently undermine people in STEM fields. Growing up with parents who had limited formal education, I never felt the pressure to prove myself in math or science—my parents just wanted me to be safe and grounded. But now, as a carpenter in Los Angeles, I've noticed how the same stereotypes that make people question their abilities in math or physics can also make them question their place in the world. Stereotype threat isn't just about being called 'not smart enough'—it's the quiet anxiety that keeps people from even trying. For example, when I was teaching my kids about basic engineering concepts, I saw how their confidence wavered when they thought they were 'not the type' to handle complex problems. This is especially true for women and people of color in STEM, who often face a double burden of proving themselves against both gender and racial biases. We need to address this by creating spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes without judgment. In my community, I've started small by organizing workshops for local teens where they can explore engineering through hands-on projects without the pressure of standardized tests. It's not about fixing the problem but about building trust and showing that everyone has a place in STEM, regardless of their background. My depression has made me more aware of how these invisible barriers can chip away at someone's self-worth, so I'm trying to model resilience by focusing on the process, not the outcome.",
